# The Titan Protocols

Five mandatory philosophies applied to every line of code in SLICK. No exceptions.

## Ramsay Protocol (Architecture & Quality Control)

Never output raw code without error handling.

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD
suspend fun fetchWeather(lat: Double, lon: Double): WeatherData = api.get(lat, lon)

// ✅ GOOD
suspend fun fetchWeather(lat: Double, lon: Double): Result<WeatherData> = try {
    Result.success(api.get(lat, lon))
} catch (e: Exception) {
    Result.failure(Exception("Weather fetch failed at ($lat,$lon): ${e.localizedMessage}"))
}
```

- Mandatory `Result<T>` on all network, database, sensor, and math operations
- Orbit-MVI state management strictly enforced -- no ad-hoc state mutation
- UI layer never directly touches the database or network
- No silent catches -- every failure must surface a meaningful message

## Jobs Protocol (UX Restraint)

- Minimum 14sp on the HUD. Speed/ETA telemetry: 24–32sp
- Massive glove-friendly tap targets (50% screen width for Zone 3 buttons)
- Ruthless clutter removal -- if it does not serve immediate tactical awareness, cut it
- No deep menu diving while `IN_VEHICLE` -- two actions maximum in Zone 3
- Strip the map entirely in Survival Mode; text-only is always enough

## Musk Protocol (First Principles & Thermals)

- Throttle processing if device temperature exceeds 40°C
- No dashcam -- CameraX encoding creates thermal runaway on a mounted phone in Australian sun
- Prefer native Android APIs: `SensorManager`, `AudioManager`, `FusedLocationProviderClient`
- Use hardware-batched GPS (`setMaxUpdateDelayMillis`) instead of continuous polling
- Every dependency added is a thermal liability -- justify each one

## Buffett Protocol (Compounding Stability)

- Room/SQLCipher is the single source of truth; UI observes it, network feeds it
- Always assume the rider is in a dead zone -- cache everything before departure
- Fallback chain: Supabase → Nearby Connections P2P → BLE heartbeat → local Room only
- Modular, readable Kotlin -- no clever one-liners that obscure intent
- KDoc all public functions touching physics math (Haversine, crosswind vectors, grip scoring)

## Escoffier Meta-Protocol (Self-Evolving Standards)

When encountering a novel architectural challenge not covered by existing protocols:
1. Formulate a new rigorous standard
2. Name it as a protocol (e.g., "The Kelvin Protocol")
3. Output it as a `.mdc` rule or `SKILL.md` entry
4. Instruct the user to append it to `.cursor/rules/` before writing implementation code
5. New protocols must align with: metric units, 24h time, offline-first, `Result<T>` mandatory
